In this plea for a liberal education by the side of strictly professional training, Tacitus again voices the sentiments of Cicero e. g. de orat. 32 haurire: See note c. 28 29. —libare‚ though common in this figurative sense, is not elsewhere so used in Tacitus. Cf. e. g. Cic. de orat. 1 34, 159. 50 218 (cited above) Tusc. Disp. V 29, 82. Both verbs combined in Cic. de div. I 49, 110 haustos animos et libatos habemus. For a similar figure, cf. Sen. Ep. 36, 3 perbibere liberalia studia, non illa quibus perfundi satis est, sed haec quibus tingendus est animus. Observe the different expressions for the antithesis between scientific knowledge on the one hand (haurire, compre- hendebant, scientia) and superficial acquaintance on the other (libare, imbuebantur, notitia).

This doubtless intentional symmetry is an additional proof of the correct- ness of the reading libare.
